\section*{Notes}
\label{sec-1}
\subsection*{Section 1}
\label{sec-1_1}
\subsubsection*{Introduction}
\label{sec-1_1_1}

Logic has essentially to do with reasoning and truth.
\begin{itemize}

\item Inference, Truth and Validity\\
\label{sec-1_1_1_1}%
The fundamental focus of logic is on \emph{inference} or \emph{argument}.\\

The premises of an argument are supposed to lend rational support to the conclusion in the sense that anyone who accepts the premises and is faced with the argument must, on pain of irrationality, accept the conclusion.\\

Logic investigates the abstract conditions of rationality by classifying and studying \emph{forms} of argument.\\

There is a difference between \emph{validity} and \emph{truth}: sentences (statements, propositions, assumptions, etc.\) are true or false; arguments (inferences, passages of reasoning) are valid or invalid.\\

To say that an argument is valid means that it is \emph{impossible} for its premises to be true and its conclusion false. Conversely, an argument is invalid if there is a way for its premises to be true and its conclusion false.

\item Inference in the Abstract\\
\label{sec-1_1_1_2}%
Validity of inferences or potential inferences is a \emph{relation} between premises and conclusion. This is a relation of \emph{logical consequence}. Important properties \emph{any} relation of logical consequence defined over any language have are:
\begin{itemize}

\item \textbf{Reflexivity}:\\
\label{sec-1_1_1_2_1}%
$X \vdash A$ if $A$ is a member of $X$. In particular $A \vdash A$. This is obviously valid: if $A$ is in the database $X$ then the query $A$ succeeds without requiring any inference steps. There is no way for everything in $X$ to be true without $A$ being true if $A$ happens to be one of the things in $X$.

\item \textbf{Monotonicity}:\\
\label{sec-1_1_1_2_2}%
If $X \vdash A$ then for any bigger set $Y$ of which $X$ is a subset, $Y \vdash A$. This means that whatever follows from just some of the assumptions or data follows from the set, or in other words that adding more information cannot destroy any inferences.

\item \textbf{Transitivity}:\\
\label{sec-1_1_1_2_3}%
If $X \vdash A$ for \emph{every} $A$ in $Y$, and if $Y \vdash B$, then $X \vdash B$. This is a familiar idea: if you can derive some lemmas from the axioms of a theory, and then derive a theorem from the lemmas, you can chain the arguments together to obtain a derivation of the theorem from the axioms. This important principle is often called ``cut'' in the literature of proof theory.
\end{itemize} % ends low level
\end{itemize} % ends low level
\subsubsection*{Connectives}
\label{sec-1_1_2}

Every occurrence of a connective in a formula has a \emph{scope}. Its scope is defined to be the shortest formula (or subformula) in which that occurrence lies.
