\subsection*{Section 7}
\label{sec-1_7}
\subsubsection*{Identity}
\label{sec-1_7_1}

Extending first-order logic with the ability to describe things as identical (or different). To do this we add the relation of \emph{equality} or $=$ - this symbolises a relation, the trivial relation which everything has to itself and nothing has to anything else.\\

Identical is meant here in the strict sense of ``one and the same'' - not just ``exactly similar''.\\

Do not confuse the ``is'' of identity (as in ``Hesperus \emph{is} Phosphorus'') with the copula, or ``is'' of predication. In the latter, the use of ``is'' is as the application of an object to its predicate (as in ``Tasmania is no place for the feint-hearted'' expressed for instance as $Ft$). In the former, the use of ``is'' is used to assert that two objects are in fact not distinct, but share the same \emph{reference}.\\

The addition of a notation for identity has greatly increased the expressive power of (the limited language of) first-order logic. Without identity we can formalise, for example, ``Ted is running'' as $Rt$, and claims such as ``someone runs faster than Ted'' as $\exists x Fxt$ but not much else in the limited vocabulary. \emph{With} identity though, we can say:\\

``Ted alone is running'' as $Rt \land (\forall x\{Rx\})x = t$.

``Everyone other than Ted is running'' as $(\forall x\{x \ne t\})Rx$.

``Ted is the fastest'' as $(\forall x\{x \ne t\})Ftx$.

``There is more than one runner'' as $(\exists x\{Rx\})(\exists y\{Ry\})x \ne y$.\\

In English, adjectives which admit of degrees give rise to both comparative and superlative forms. The comparative form may be formalised as a two-place relation between objects, and thus the logic of comparatives can be studied as a subject in its own right. The superlative form is systematically related to the comparative form. To express this relationship we need to be able to say ``other'', for which we are able to use ``$\ne$". Thus the identity symbol yields a reduction of the logic of superlatives to that of the comparative which in turn can be represented in the calculus of relations. This effect is \emph{explanatory} and a conceptual simplification.\\

Without identity we cannot talk of the quantity of objects which satisfy some problem beyond ``there is one'' or ``there is many''. With the addition of identity to our language, we can easily model the fact that two (or indeed, any distinct number of) objects satisfy some property. In this way, we are able to more easily speak of \emph{existence}.\\

Generally, to say that there are more then $n$ (i.e. at least $n+1$) $F$'s:

$(\forall x_1)\ldots(\forall x_n)(\exists y\{Fy\})(x_1 \ne y \land \ldots \land x_n \ne y)$
